{
  "text": "These specific inclusion criteria may, in part, explain the low success rate (10%) we obtained with the fibrin glue treatment, since our surgical technique does not differ from techniques used by other authors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Our results are in line with the findings of BUCHANAN et al. [CITATION_4] , who studied 22 patients with complex cryptoglandular fistulas submitted to fibrin glue injection. Their study included 19 patients (86.5%) with transsphincteric fistulas, 1 patient (4.5%) with a suprasphicteric fistula, and 1 patient (4.5%) with an extrasphincteric fistula. After a follow-up period of 16 moths, only 3 patients (14%) did not develop fistula recurrence, remaining asymptomatic. Similarly, LOUNGNARATH et al. [CITATION_5] reviewed their experience with the fibrin glue treatment of 39 patients with complex anal fistulas. The healing rate for fistulas of cryptoglandular origin was 23% (5 of 22 patients).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "24608313",
    "[CITATION_2]": "204100917",
